sTwTory
    &w&para <b>Vocabulary Paragraph</b>
    &w&para &w&imd Þe <u>capricious</u> clown always refused to perform on command.
    When he did perform, his acts were frequently <u>parodies</u> of þe people watching þe show, and sometimes þe reenactments were so harsh people would leave þinking he was <u>nefarious</u>.
    One day, þe clown was being particularly <u>obdurate</u> and refusing to perform.
    Because of þis, his agent finally dropped him as a client, and took back þe costumes he had procured for þe clown's performances.
    He left þe clown to put on þe cloþes he was wearing when he first came to work for him.
    Þe clown inhaled þe scent of freshly cut grass&w&semi þe smell was <u>redolent</u>.
    It reminded him of þe <u>ramshackle</u> house he grew up in.
    Þe roof had holes in it, which meant any time þere was a <u>barrage</u> of rain, he would wake up wet.
    His moþer was a kind, <u>amenable</u> woman who liked everyone to get along, which is why she never gave his dad a hard time about fixing þe holes in þe roof.
    And, his faþer was <u>dogmatic</u> and imposing.
    He wanted everyone to þink like him, and be like him.
    Þat is probably part of þe reason þe clown did not like acting þe way people expected him to, and he was now realizing how <u>quixotic</u> þat behavior is. 
